{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505775","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505775"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:35:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:35:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2478"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2478","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2478"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.23,0.16,0.5,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2478"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113161"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2478","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2478"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2478"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95188"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"483"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1815"},{"type":"tags","id":"2701"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2130"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2134"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15939"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16654"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43164"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46467"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113161","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113161"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents with a history of shortness of breath and productive cough with white sputum for the last 2 years. He reports that the shortness of breath was brought on by exertion but recently it has worsened and persists even while resting. He does not have chest pain. He has a past medical history of diabetes mellitus and hypertension. He stopped smoking last year but has a history of smoking one pack of cigarettes daily for 38 years. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChest auscultation reveals bilaterally decreased breath sounds and expiratory wheezes. Heart sounds are muffled but regular. The results of his full blood count is as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaematocrit = 54% \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets = 310 x 109/L \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELeucocytes = 9.8 x 109/L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most suggestive of the need for long-term oxygen therapy in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Arterial carbon dioxide tension \u003E40 mmHg","Arterial oxygen tension \u003C65 mmHg","FEV1/FVC ratio \u003C50%","Oxygen saturation \u003C88%","Respiratory rate of \u003E30/min"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient with chronic cough, dyspnoea, bilaterally decreased breath sounds with expiratory wheezes and distant heart sounds most likely has \u003Cstrong\u003Echronic obstructive pulmonary disease \u003C/strong\u003E(COPD). COPD is characterized by an obstruction of the airway due to small airway inflammation. The most common risk factor for COPD is smoking. COPD generally manifests in patients aged \u0026gt;60 years who have a lifelong history of smoking. Patients typically present with dyspnoea, productive cough, prolonged expiratory phase, and cyanosis. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile the mainstay of treatment is bronchodilators and inhaled corticosteroids, long-term oxygen therapy is indicated in a specific group of patients and it has been shown to improve the mortality of such patients. Long-term supplemental oxygen in COPD patients is indicated if they have at least one of the following:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOxygen saturation (SpO2) of \u226488% on room air\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EArterial oxygen tension (PaO2) of \u226455 mmHg on room air\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESpO2 of \u226489% or PaO2 of \u226459 mmHg if there is evidence of right heart failure, pulmonary hypertension, or polycythaemia (ie, haematocrit \u0026gt;55%).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a haematocrit of 54%. Hence, the primary indication of long-term oxygen therapy in his case is \u003Cstrong\u003Eoxygen saturation \u0026lt;88%\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMost COPD patients have chronic hypercapnia, low FEV1/FVC ratio, and high respiratory rate. However, these findings are not indications to initiate long-term oxygen therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EArterial oxygen tension of \u226459 mmHg is an indication to start long-term oxygen therapy in patients with polycythaemia (not PaO2 of \u0026lt;65 mmHg). Increased carboxyhemoglobin (COHb) in active smokers and chronic hypoxemia in COPD patients are proposed to contribute to the development of secondary polycythemia, leading to an elevated haematocrit on a full blood count. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["One indication of long-term oxygen therapy in a patient with COPD is SpO2 of \u003C88%."],"references":["McDonald CF. Oxygen therapy for COPD. J Thorac Dis. 2014;6(11):1632-1639. doi:10.3978/j.issn.2072-1439.2014.10.23. Available from: https://jtd.amegroups.org/article/view/3495/html","McDonald CF. Home oxygen therapy. Aust Prescr. 2022;45(1):21-24. doi:10.18773/austprescr.2022.007. Available from: https://australianprescriber.tg.org.au/articles/home-oxygen-therapy.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95188"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2478"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95188","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95188"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-10T09:06:10+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-10T09:06:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2478"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113161"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},